Metabolite identification

Introduction

In this tutorial, we will perform metabolite identification using the metabom8 package in R. We will focus on the STOCSY (STOichometric correlation SpectroscopY) method, which allows us to identify correlations between metabolites in NMR spectral data.

Prerequisites

Ensure that you have the following libraries installed:

install.packages("metabom8")
install.packages("readr")
install.packages("ggplot2")

Setting Up the Environment

Let’s set our working directory and load the necessary libraries.

setwd('/Volumes/AEIWZ A/Project/AG-Bio')
library(metabom8)
library(readr)
## Warning: package 'readr' was built under R version 4.2.3
## 
## Attaching package: 'readr'
## The following object is masked from 'package:metabom8':
## 
##     spec
library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.2.3

Loading the Data

We will load the NMR data, chemical shift values (ppm), and metadata from URLs:

# Load data
X = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/leaf_norm.csv')
ppm = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/leaf_ppm.csv')
meta = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/Metadata.csv')

# Convert X to matrix
X = as.matrix(X)

# Convert ppm to numeric
ppm = as.numeric(ppm)

# Set column names for X
colnames(X) = ppm

# Data cleaning
X = na.omit(X)

Visualizing Spectra

Let’s visualize the NMR spectra to gain insight into the data:

matspec(X, ppm, shift = range(ppm), interactive = F)

STOCSY Analysis

We will define a driver peak and perform the STOCSY analysis. The driver peak is a specific ppm value to which we will correlate other spectral variables.

# Define driver peak
driver1 = 3.6044

# Perform STOCSY analysis
stocsy_model = stocsy(X, ppm, driver1)

Plotting STOCSY Results

We can visualize the STOCSY results to identify correlations:

# Zoom-in on different plot regions
plotStocsy(stocsy_model, shift = range(ppm))

plotStocsy(stocsy_model, shift = c(3, 4))
